@flexiarg war-room/wr-4-inhabit-before-building
@title WR-4: Inhabit Before Building
@sigils [⚖/令]
@audience futon stack operators, agents, mission authors
@tone foundational
@style pattern

! conclusion: Inhabit the surfaces that already exist before building new infrastructure; new infrastructure is justified only when it makes an existing surface more inhabitable.

  + context: War Room decision WR-4 (2026-04-10). Operator: Joe. A cross-futon ruling on where effort goes when the stack is infrastructure-rich but usage-poor.

  + IF:
    The stack has extensive infrastructure: Agency, evidence stores, pattern libraries, Arxana browser, candidate invariant queues, mission documents, excursion logs, Bayesian models, context retrieval.

  + HOWEVER:
    Most of this infrastructure is uninhabited. The Candidate Invariant queue has sixty-five entries with no processing pipeline, the evidence browser was disconnected, excursions are explorations without missions, and the primary coding surface generated no evidence until today.

  + THEN:
    The next phase is inhabitation, not construction. New infrastructure is justified only when it directly serves inhabitation of existing surfaces. The three workstreams, mathematics, consulting, and stack inhabitation, must be mutually reinforcing: stack work that does not serve mathematics or consulting is pi-hermit mode, building alone and never depositing, and violates the cargo-implies-depositing constraint.

  + BECAUSE:
    Surface earns inhabitation: uninhabited infrastructure is dead infrastructure. Inhabitation feeds evolution: without inhabitation the Baldwin loop starves. The JSDQ diagnosis shows the same pattern at the personal level: high cargo, low reserves, mode stuck on foraging. External depositing and internal stack inhabitation require the same policy transition, from scholar to consultant to free-solo.

    + evidence: Bulletin 6 found the evidence loop was ninety percent built, the last tenth wiring and friction reduction. The JSDQ terminal vocabulary names three constraint violations, cargo-implies-depositing, signal-implies-follow-up, and deadline-implies-urgency, all pointing at depositing. The M-stack-inhabitation portfolio has ten surfaces, most uninhabited.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Before starting any new infrastructure mission, ask which existing surface it makes more inhabitable. If the answer is none, defer the mission until this ruling is satisfied.
